{{refimprove|date=December 2010}}
[[File:AberdeenBestiaryFol56rPhoenix.jpg|thumb|180px|Folio 56 recto of the ''Aberdeen Bestiary'' has a [[miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniature]] of the [[Phoenix (mythology)|Phoenix]]]]

The '''''Aberdeen Bestiary''''' ([[Aberdeen University]] Library, Univ Lib. MS 24) is a 12th-century English [[illuminated manuscript]] [[bestiary]] that was first listed in 1542 in the inventory of the [[Old Royal Library]] at the [[Palace of Westminster]]. 

Information about its origins and patron are circumstantial. It probably comes from the 12th century and was owned by an ecclesiastical patron of the north or south province. The ''Aberdeen Bestiary'' is related to other [[bestiary|bestiaries]] of the [[Middle Ages]] and especially the ''[[Ashmole Bestiary]]''. Some argue that the ''Aberdeen Bestiary'' might be the older of the two.{{Who|date=July 2010}}

